<subSubSection id="1AD0FDA0F7955892F82EAAB09631E7C3" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="D9635AE59601C81D93A87B787EF5CBA0" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8715471D4BBA6EF1553B3EE9182A4F2B" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">
<taxonomicName id="6D9E74F783F4292707F6D4D9FEB49376" authorityName="G. Heringer, Salino &amp; Valdespino" authorityYear="2015" class="Lycopodiopsida" family="Selaginellaceae" genus="Selaginella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Selaginella alstonii" order="Selaginellales" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Lycopodiophyta" rank="species" species="alstonii">
<emphasis id="F4AF28DE9CD275F51DA77B6A669E02E4" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Selaginella alstonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to subg. 
<taxonomicName id="7ED620A767137D6B5905969F7BEFDFD7" class="Lycopodiopsida" family="Selaginellaceae" genus="Selaginella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="(Stachygynandrum)" order="Selaginellales" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Lycopodiophyta" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Stachygynandrum">
<emphasis id="E7D60BEE3BDCE9ABC39C21287AA932F2" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Stachygynandrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and is characterized by its oblong to oblong-lanceolate lateral leaves with acroscopic margins short-ciliate along proximal ⅓-
<normalizedToken id="D77FB7897461FA50BA23A525FF14CFC5" originalValue="½">1/2</normalizedToken>
and elliptic to elliptic-lanceolate or ovate-elliptic median leaves with oblique bases (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="2A1A1CBBEBDEBEFA6D19DE51D0698848" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Selaginella alstonii G. Heringer, Salino &amp; Valdespino. A Section of upper surface of stem B Upper surface of median leaf C Section of lower surface of stem D Lower surface of lateral leaf. A-D taken from isotype, Almeida et al. 533 (PMA)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.50.4873.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/45213" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">1</figureCitation>
). Dried specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="F978A2F90F9F8BB772D70929753C361E" authorityName="G. Heringer, Salino &amp; Valdespino" authorityYear="2015" class="Lycopodiopsida" family="Selaginellaceae" genus="Selaginella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Selaginella alstonii" order="Selaginellales" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Lycopodiophyta" rank="species" species="alstonii">
<emphasis id="900CED726D60A0CFA6C1C08A7CF6A6D2" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Selaginella alstonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
tend to develop a groove along midribs of lateral leaves (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="9DCA7A89BB6525C22F7CDDDB5D85CB8A" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Selaginella alstonii G. Heringer, Salino &amp; Valdespino. A Section of upper surface of stem B Upper surface of median leaf C Section of lower surface of stem D Lower surface of lateral leaf. A-D taken from isotype, Almeida et al. 533 (PMA)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.50.4873.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/45213" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">1A</figureCitation>
), but it remains to be confirmed if this is a character observed in living plants or an artifact when plants are dried. The surfaces of the median and lateral leaves of 
<taxonomicName id="6C189FDC4A46E20F13E9696910E1F869" authorityName="G. Heringer, Salino &amp; Valdespino" authorityYear="2015" class="Lycopodiopsida" family="Selaginellaceae" genus="Selaginella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Selaginella alstonii" order="Selaginellales" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Lycopodiophyta" rank="species" species="alstonii">
<emphasis id="F7FF51A50B50EE047072ED72DE27D39F" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Selaginella alstonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
do not show conspicuous idioblasts when observed with a stereoscope, but on SEM micrographs, idioblast-like, papillate elongate cells are observed on the lower surfaces of lateral leaves, with papillae in 1 row over each cell lumen, parallel to the midribs (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="805767DC51288C080980B4FCA2D2FB86" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Selaginella alstonii G. Heringer, Salino &amp; Valdespino. A Section of upper surface of stem B Upper surface of median leaf C Section of lower surface of stem D Lower surface of lateral leaf. A-D taken from isotype, Almeida et al. 533 (PMA)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.50.4873.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/45213" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">1D</figureCitation>
). Additionally, in some median leaves, the outer bases have 2-4 short cilia. In some plants of 
<taxonomicName id="F41D6E09F30BC1E10252B1B1D2A33C6D" authorityName="G. Heringer, Salino &amp; Valdespino" authorityYear="2015" class="Lycopodiopsida" family="Selaginellaceae" genus="Selaginella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Selaginella alstonii" order="Selaginellales" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Lycopodiophyta" rank="species" species="alstonii">
<emphasis id="56A2201BD2CD20692276D425E1728D83" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Selaginella alstonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as well as in 
<taxonomicName id="33437DF7AED0FF4807192AC03D7BE6D4" authorityName="Valdespino" authorityYear="2015" class="Lycopodiopsida" family="Selaginellaceae" genus="Selaginella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Selaginella saltuicola" order="Selaginellales" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Lycopodiophyta" rank="species" species="saltuicola">
<emphasis id="3039B18CC9F65117E88D353BEB1704BE" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Selaginella saltuicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(which see for discussion), we observed vegetative growth from the tips of some strobili.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="95CB4B68AB78AFDA1B65BA250CB766D2" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">
<taxonomicName id="936FA36AA45BC75EEA149FC95E34BE53" authorityName="G. Heringer, Salino &amp; Valdespino" authorityYear="2015" class="Lycopodiopsida" family="Selaginellaceae" genus="Selaginella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Selaginella alstonii" order="Selaginellales" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Lycopodiophyta" rank="species" species="alstonii">
<emphasis id="5F3796049F705405525C7F18B3CDB957" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Selaginella alstonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName id="9997BCA186A7A920AC0BF67F7FC24851" authorityName="Bak" authorityYear="1883" class="Lycopodiopsida" family="Selaginellaceae" genus="Selaginella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Selaginella acanthostachys" order="Selaginellales" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Lycopodiophyta" rank="species" species="acanthostachys">
<emphasis id="11699D44C62B419979CD67F0ED38BC61" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Selaginella acanthostachys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Colombia, Ecuador, and Peru; however the characters given in the diagnosis separate them. Among other species of 
<taxonomicName id="EEDE65479A8219BE68ADC587B13E77CC" class="Lycopodiopsida" family="Selaginellaceae" genus="Selaginella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Selaginella" order="Selaginellales" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Lycopodiophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="14DDE24E9B14709396F1C4E0570CF7DA" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Selaginella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Minas Gerais, 
<taxonomicName id="679824C918D6FE2FADB07408DA25C061" authorityName="G. Heringer, Salino &amp; Valdespino" authorityYear="2015" class="Lycopodiopsida" family="Selaginellaceae" genus="Selaginella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Selaginella alstonii" order="Selaginellales" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Lycopodiophyta" rank="species" species="alstonii">
<emphasis id="4569DB91323CAE0FE417867A7C7A1019" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Selaginella alstonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be confused with 
<taxonomicName id="DD122BF4D1719EEBC3E4873D39D32987" class="Lycopodiopsida" family="Selaginellaceae" genus="Selaginella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Selaginella decomposita" order="Selaginellales" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Lycopodiophyta" rank="species" species="decomposita">
<emphasis id="087E7E2C7FC69AB5BA05154C8A24AF3C" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Selaginella decomposita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Spring because of their similar texture and shape of the lateral leaves. 
<taxonomicName id="E1AA6A338C02162429F056338BBB1D09" class="Lycopodiopsida" family="Selaginellaceae" genus="Selaginella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Selaginella decomposita" order="Selaginellales" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Lycopodiophyta" rank="species" species="decomposita">
<emphasis id="B69AF53B4E4065149ECBCFEBA32C7F33" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Selaginella decomposita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however, has an ascending to erect habit and is a more robust plant.
</paragraph>
